  <setup>
    <selectFromSequence name="a" from="4" to="7" step="1"/>
    <selectFromSequence name="b" from="4" to="7" step="1" exclude="$a"/>
    <selectFromSequence name="c" from="2" to="5" step="1" exclude="$a $b"/>

    <!--
    <math name="P">($c*$a+$d)/($a-$b)</math>
    <math name="Q">($c*$b+$d)/($b-$a)</math>    
    -->
    
    <mathList name="PFdecomp">($a*x)/(x^2 + $c^2) ($b)/(x^2 + $c^2)</mathList>
    <mathList name="PFdecompEntered">$PF1 $PF2</mathList>

    <math name="u">x^2 + $c^2</math>
    <math name="du">2x</math>
    
    <function name="f" symbolic="false" >
      ($a*x+$b)/(x^2 + $c^2)
    </function> 

    <function name="F" symbolic="false" >
     $a/2*ln(x^2 + $c^2) + $b/$c*atan(x/$c)
    </function>   
    <function name="Fa" symbolic="false" >
     $a/2*ln(abs(x^2 + $c^2)) + $b/$c*atan(x/$c)
    </function>   

    <function name="int1a" symbolic="false" >
     $a/2*ln(x^2 + $c^2)
    </function>   
    <function name="int1b" symbolic="false" >
     $a/2*ln(abs(x^2 + $c^2))
    </function>   

    <function name="int2" symbolic="false" >
     $b/$c*atan(x/$c)
    </function>  
    
    <boolean name="correctPFfound">$PFfound.creditAchieved=1</boolean>
    
  </setup>

<p>
  Consider the indefinite integral
  <me>
    \int \frac{$a x + $b}{x^2 + <math simplify>$c^2</math>} \, dx
  </me>
  Integrals of this form arise regularly when using partial fractions.  Notice that the denominator of the integrand can't be factored, but we can still use algebra to rewrite the integrand.
</p>

<p>
  First, use the distributive property of division to write the integrand as a sum of two fractions, and hence the original integral as a sum of two integrals.
</p>  

<p>
  <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{$a x + $b}{x^2 + <math simplify>$c^2</math>} \, dx = \int </m><mathInput minWidth="75" name="PF1"/> <m>\displaystyle dx + \int </m> <mathInput minWidth="75" name="PF2"/> <m>dx </m> <answer name="PFfound" unorderedCompare><award><when>$PFdecomp = $PFdecompEntered</when></award></answer>
</p>  

<p hide="$correctPFfound">
  (<em>Once you have the correct decomposition above, additional prompts will appear.</em>)
</p>
<p hide="not $correctPFfound">
  <p>
    There are now two separate integrals to evaluate and they require different approaches.  We will wait to include the arbitrary <q><m>+C</m></q> until the final conclusion of our work.
  </p>
  <p>
    For <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{$a x}{x^2 + <math simplify>$c^2</math>} \, dx</m>, observe that this integral may be evaluated using <m>u</m>-substitution with the substitution <m>u = </m><mathInput name="uChoice"/>, <m>du = </m><mathInput name="duChoice"/> <m>dx</m> <answer><award><when>$uChoice=$u and $duChoice=$du</when></award></answer>.  Use your substitution to evaluate this first integral and enter your result below.
  </p>
  <p>
    <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{$a x}{x^2 + <math simplify>$c^2</math>} \, dx = </m><mathInput name="int1Entered"/><answer><award><when>$int1a = $int1Entered or $int1b = $int1Entered </when></award></answer>
  </p> 

  <p>
    For <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{$b}{x^2 + <math simplify>$c^2</math>} \, dx</m>, this integral is closely related to 
    <me>
      \int \frac{1}{x^2 + 1} dx = \arctan(x).
    </me>
    With the substitution <m>u = \frac{x}{a}</m>, it can be shown that 
    <me>
      \int \frac{1}{x^2 + a^2} dx = \arctan\left(\frac{x}{a}\right).
    </me>
    Use this latest result to now evaluate <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{$b}{x^2 + <math simplify>$c^2</math>} \, dx</m> and enter your result in the provided blank.   
  </p>
  <p>
    <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{$b}{x^2 + <math simplify>$c^2</math>} \, dx = </m><mathInput name="int2Entered"/><answer><award><when>$int2 = $int2Entered </when></award></answer>
  </p> 

  <p>
   Finally, put all of your preceding work together to evaluate the original integral.
  </p>
  <p>
    <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{$a x + $b}{x^2 + <math simplify>$c^2</math>} \, dx = </m><mathInput minWidth="150" name="Fentered"/> <m>+ \, C \,</m><answer><award><when>$F = $Fentered</when></award></answer>
  </p>
  
</p>
